      <h4 class="panel-title">
        <a role="button" data-toggle="collapse" data-parent="#accordion" href="#collapseTwo" aria-expanded="true" aria-controls="collapseTwo">
          Make Your Yeast Starter
          <div class="pull-right">1/15/2016</div>
        </a>
      </h4>
    </div>
    <div id="collapseTwo" class="panel-collapse collapse in" role="tabpanel" aria-labelledby="headingTwo">
      <div class="panel-body">
        <p>At least a few hours before, ideally a day ahead of time, you'll want to make a yeast starter. Yeast can be pitched as is, especially if you get one of the Wyeast smack packs, but you should always make a starter regardless. It'll ensure you have a huge, healthy yeast colony which gets fermentation started faster and finish more completely.</p>
        <p>You'll never regret making a starter. Seriously.</p>

        <p>To make one, you'll need:</p>
        <ul>
        <li>Your yeast packet</li>
        <li>A glass growler (no lids!)</li>
        <li>Sanitizer</li>
        <li>1/4 cup of light dry malt extract</li>
        <li>1 qt cold clear water</li>
        <li>A saucepan</li>
        <li>Ice</li>
        </ul>

        <p><strong>The day before your brew day</strong>, activate your yeast pack (if you're using Wyeast).</p>
        <p>Start boiling 1qt of cold, clear water in your saucepan.</p>
        <p>Once boiling, remove from heat, and stir in the 1/4 cup of DME and stir in well to combine.</p>
        <p>Add back to the heat and boil for 10 minutes.</p>
        <p>In the meantime, sanitize your growler, a pair of scissors, and a funnel. You'll also want to sanitize the the outside of your yeast pack.</p>
        <p>Once your boil is complete, move your saucepan to the sink and chill it in an ice bath until it's below 80F.</p>
        <p>Pour the now chilled wort into your sanitized growler using the sanitized funnel.
        <p>Add your yeast pack to the growler, cover, and shake up vigorously.
        <p>Cover the top of the growler loosely with foil. <strong>Make sure not to use the growler cap</strong>.</p>
        <p>Leave this container out at room temperature, shaking it every now and then until you're ready to brew.</p>
        <p>If you've made this a day in advance, you'll want to throw this growler in the refrigerator for a few hours right before you start your brew day.</p>
        <p>Once chilled, decant off the majority of the wort, and leave just the yeasty slurry at the bottom. This isn't required, but do it if you can. This will help ensure the not-so-tasty starter beer doesn't affect your final beer result.</p>
        <p>After decanting, leave the growler out to warm back to room temperature while you're brewing.</p>
